00:44:57,364 --> 00:45:01,068
and Khadija and the children
moved into this street.

646
00:45:01,368 --> 00:45:03,904
And this became a little Muslim ghetto.

647
00:45:05,005 --> 00:45:06,573
And this leads to real hardship.

648
00:45:06,640 --> 00:45:09,276
There's a period of time where
according to the tradition

649
00:45:09,276 --> 00:45:12,145
they're actually eating
from the leaves of trees.

650
00:45:13,347 --> 00:45:16,116
Famine destroyed
the fortunes of Muhammad's

651
00:45:16,116 --> 00:45:19,686
protector, Abu Talib,
and his follower Abu Bakr.

652
00:45:21,321 --> 00:45:25,592
The survival of both the clan and
Islam were in jeopardy.

653
00:45:28,028 --> 00:45:32,366
But for Muhammad the damage
hit even closer to home.

654
00:45:33,233 --> 00:45:36,370
Khadija, Muhammad's beloved wife, uh

655
00:45:36,370 --> 00:45:40,674
perhaps weakened by the privations,
actually died.

656
00:45:42,309 --> 00:45:45,546
And that was just
a crippling blow for him.

657
00:45:45,746 --> 00:45:49,183
Left him feeling alone and
vulnerable and weak.

658
00:45:50,017 --> 00:45:52,452
He would miss her all his life,
I think.

659
00:45:55,088 --> 00:45:58,959
Then the catastrophe happened
that Abu Talib died.

660
00:45:59,860 --> 00:46:03,497
Perhaps himself weakened
by the deprivation in food.

661
00:46:04,965 --> 00:46:07,067
Now without Abu Talib

662
00:46:07,568 --> 00:46:10,204
Muhammad was fair game for assassination.

663
00:46:12,272 --> 00:46:14,808
And there's a terrible moment where

664
00:46:14,842 --> 00:46:16,944
he utters this heart breaking prayer

665
00:46:17,177 --> 00:46:20,781
saying oh my god I have no other
protector but you, Allah.

666
00:46:21,348 --> 00:46:23,784
And how was he going to move forward?

667
00:46:24,985 --> 00:46:28,155
He'd done what Allah had told him to do.

668
00:46:28,155 --> 00:46:30,057
He had proclaimed this message and

669
00:46:30,057 --> 00:46:33,961
all that he seemed to have done was
stir up hostility and hatred.

670
00:46:34,361 --> 00:46:37,564
Um and split his tribe down the middle

671
00:46:37,564 --> 00:46:39,333
this wasn't improving matters.

672
00:46:39,967 --> 00:46:44,805
He must have felt an almost,
a sort of a dark night of the soul.

673
00:46:45,339 --> 00:46:48,909
He is at the low point of his mission.

674
00:46:49,076 --> 00:46:53,313
He's been almost 13 years now in Mecca and

675
00:46:53,313 --> 00:46:58,752
the results are not,
they are not impressive.

676
00:47:01,021 --> 00:47:03,156
But at this point, at this low ebb

677
00:47:03,390 --> 00:47:06,560
he is now being prepared

678
00:47:06,627 --> 00:47:09,596
for the most extraordinary
mystical experience

679
00:47:09,763 --> 00:47:11,832
of his prophetic life

680
00:47:11,965 --> 00:47:15,802
and that is what is known
as the night ascension.

681
00:47:18,038 --> 00:47:21,708
The story goes that one night
he was sleeping near the Ka'aba

682
00:47:22,643 --> 00:47:26,346
and he was woken from sleep by Gabriel

683
00:47:26,780 --> 00:47:30,784
who mounted him on a Buraq

684
00:47:30,784 --> 00:47:33,453
a magical stead

685
00:47:34,254 --> 00:47:38,292
and they flew from Mecca to Jerusalem.

686
00:47:43,063 --> 00:47:45,599
And then he began an ascent.

687
00:47:45,832 --> 00:47:49,036
Up through the seven heavens
to the divine throne

688
00:47:49,603 --> 00:47:54,875
at every stage of the heavens
he meets various prophets of the past.

689
00:47:55,008 --> 00:47:59,546
He meets Abraham, he meets Jesus,
and John the Baptist.

690
00:47:59,980 --> 00:48:01,548
He meets Moses

691
00:48:03,050 --> 00:48:06,720
and finally he enters into
the divine presence and there

692
00:48:07,020 --> 00:48:09,957
the sources are silent
because when you enter

693
00:48:09,957 --> 00:48:12,626
into the presence of God
you have gone beyond words.

694
00:48:13,460 --> 00:48:18,065
And he receives from God,
the highest form of knowledge and truth

695
00:48:18,799 --> 00:48:22,936
and many injunctions of the religion
itself including the final form

696
00:48:23,437 --> 00:48:28,141
of the daily prayers
Now all of this took place

697
00:48:28,976 --> 00:48:30,777
in a time beyond time.

698
00:48:31,512 --> 00:48:34,681
That's why some sources say
that as the door was

699
00:48:34,681 --> 00:48:37,584
swinging when he left,
it was still swinging when he came back.

700
00:48:39,152 --> 00:48:43,123
For later Muslims this also
meant that the departure point

701
00:48:44,091 --> 00:48:49,263
that is Jerusalem, the Dome of the Rock,
became also important.

702
00:48:50,464 --> 00:48:54,735
Many Muslims say that there are
three holy cities in Islam:

703
00:48:54,801 --> 00:48:59,106
Mecca, and Medina, the City of the Prophet,
and Jerusalem.

704
00:49:01,441 --> 00:49:04,211
When he comes back somebody asks him

705
00:49:04,678 --> 00:49:08,482
what have you been doing, he says
I went to Jerusalem last night

706
00:49:08,815 --> 00:49:11,985
and this man says,
you went to Jerusalem last night?

707
00:49:12,186 --> 00:49:14,087
Are you willing to say that publicly?

708
00:49:15,088 --> 00:49:19,560
So they assemble this group and
they tell him, describe for us

709
00:49:19,860 --> 00:49:23,964
Jerusalem and he begins
to describe it in very exact detail.

710
00:49:25,032 --> 00:49:25,999
And they're shocked.

711
00:49:25,999 --> 00:49:27,868
They don't what to make of this now.

712
00:49:29,403 --> 00:49:33,540
The story of the Night Journey not
only incited Muhammad's enemies.

713
00:49:33,941 --> 00:49:37,044
It caused doubt even among
some of his followers.

714
00:49:38,679 --> 00:49:41,882
This is something that
they hadn't really expected.

715
00:49:42,049 --> 00:49:44,585
A journey that takes them
a month to be made

716
00:49:44,785 --> 00:49:46,987
in an evening and to come back.

717
00:49:47,754 --> 00:49:50,023
What Abu Bakr says is listen

718
00:49:50,023 --> 00:49:53,126
I believe that he's getting
messages from God.

719
00:49:53,293 --> 00:49:57,731
That is certainly more extraordinary
than making a Night Journey to Jerusalem.

720
00:49:59,266 --> 00:50:03,036
As Muhammad's relationship with
the Meccans continued to deteriorate

721
00:50:03,270 --> 00:50:07,841
his enemies decided that the time
had come to eliminate him.

722
00:50:10,577 --> 00:50:13,514
And they decide to get
a youth from each clan.

723
00:50:13,780 --> 00:50:17,584
They all come together and they're going
to strike him with one blow together.

724
00:50:17,651 --> 00:50:21,088
So, the blood is distributed
amongst all the clans.

725
00:50:23,423 --> 00:50:27,995
Under cover of darkness the assassins
surrounded Muhammad's home.

726
00:50:30,564 --> 00:50:32,866
Inside a covered figure lay asleep.

727
00:50:33,967 --> 00:50:36,870
As dawn broke, they prepared to strike.

728
00:50:38,138 --> 00:50:41,175
But Muhammad had been
forewarned of the plot.

729
00:50:41,875 --> 00:50:43,544
He asked his cousin Ali

730
00:50:43,877 --> 00:50:47,347
whom he knew the Quraysh would not harm,
to take his place.

731
00:50:48,315 --> 00:50:50,984
By the time the assassins
burst into his home

732
00:50:51,151 --> 00:50:55,889
Muhammad and his companion Abu Bakr
had escaped into the desert.

733
00:51:00,027 --> 00:51:01,895
With the Meccans in hot pursuit

734
00:51:02,229 --> 00:51:05,299
they set out on a circuitous
route to the oasis

735
00:51:05,399 --> 00:51:09,503
settlement of Yathrib,
250 miles to the north.

736
00:51:10,904 --> 00:51:13,473
For several months,
Muhammad had been sending

737
00:51:13,473 --> 00:51:15,642
his followers there for refuge.

738
00:51:16,743 --> 00:51:18,979
Now, he was about to join them.

739
00:51:19,713 --> 00:51:22,482
Yathrib was quite different from Mecca.

740
00:51:23,116 --> 00:51:24,985
It was an agricultural settlement.

741
00:51:24,985 --> 00:51:29,690
People grew dates and they had
farms and there were a number

742
00:51:29,690 --> 00:51:33,160
of clans and tribes living
together in the settlement.

743
00:51:37,064 --> 00:51:42,536
The settlement was engulfed
in tribal warfare of the worst kind.

744
00:51:42,536 --> 00:51:45,105
It was an example of where the whole

745
00:51:45,105 --> 00:51:48,275
system in Arabia was beginning
to break down.

746
00:51:48,575 --> 00:51:53,981
One killing led to another and nobody
could seem to find a solution.

747
00:51:54,948 --> 00:51:57,985
Nobody, that is,
until the clans of Yathrib

748
00:51:57,985 --> 00:52:00,153
heard about the trustworthy Muhammad.

749
00:52:00,854 --> 00:52:03,690
Hoping he could unify its warring factions

750
00:52:03,824 --> 00:52:07,327
which included two major pagan
tribes and their Jewish allies

751
00:52:07,528 --> 00:52:10,831
a delegation from Yathrib
had taken the dramatic step

752
00:52:11,064 --> 00:52:13,934
of inviting Muhammad
to move to their settlement.

753
00:52:14,768 --> 00:52:18,405
The deal is that he will serve
as their binding arbitrator

754
00:52:18,672 --> 00:52:21,875
that is both sides
to the conflict have agreed

755
00:52:21,975 --> 00:52:25,279
already that they will accept
the arbitration of Muhammad

756
00:52:25,379 --> 00:52:26,580
whatever it would be.

757
00:52:27,514 --> 00:52:31,652
The people of Yathrib vowed
that they would take

758
00:52:31,652 --> 00:52:36,123
the Muslims on board as honorary
tribesmen, they would be their protectors.

759
00:52:36,256 --> 00:52:39,193
Anyone who hurt the Muslims,
they would retaliate.

760
00:52:39,226 --> 00:52:41,728
And the Muslims agreed to do the same.

761
00:52:42,696 --> 00:52:46,600
This move from your tribe

762
00:52:47,367 --> 00:52:51,338
to join up with people who were of no kin

763
00:52:51,338 --> 00:52:54,808
to you at all was absolutely unheard of.

764
00:52:55,609 --> 00:52:58,645
Muhammad was really going off
into the wilderness here

765
00:52:58,645 --> 00:53:00,914
he was breaking every tie.

766
00:53:01,114 --> 00:53:04,151
Doing something utterly
shocking and novel.

767
00:53:06,753 --> 00:53:11,558
When Prophet Muhammad was leaving
he stood up on a hill

768
00:53:12,059 --> 00:53:14,695
and he was looking on Mecca

769
00:53:15,262 --> 00:53:18,432
and his tears were coming
down out of his eyes.

770
00:53:18,899 --> 00:53:23,337
And he talked to Mecca and he said
God knows that I love you Mecca

771
00:53:23,337 --> 00:53:28,675
so much, but it is your people
who are chasing me out.

772
00:53:30,911 --> 00:53:35,115
In Yathrib, Muhammad's followers
anxiously awaited the Prophet's arrival.

773
00:53:35,716 --> 00:53:39,019
Had the man they hoped would
save them been able to save himself?

774
00:53:39,319 --> 00:53:41,755
Had the Meccans captured or
even killed him?

775
00:53:45,325 --> 00:53:48,262
When Muhammad finally reached
the outskirts of the city

776
00:53:48,662 --> 00:53:51,098
his relieved followers rushed to greet him

777
00:53:51,098 --> 00:53:55,702
with a song Muslims around
the world still sing 1400 years later.

778
00:54:06,113 --> 00:54:10,184
Oh the wise moon rose over us

779
00:54:10,350 --> 00:54:14,288
from the valley of Wadan.

780
00:54:14,521 --> 00:54:18,492
And we always do show gratefulness

781
00:54:18,692 --> 00:54:22,629
where the call is to Allah.

782
00:54:24,998 --> 00:54:28,302
Muhammad's arrival marked
the beginning of a dramatic

783
00:54:28,302 --> 00:54:30,671
new chapter in the history of Islam.

784
00:54:31,038 --> 00:54:32,139
For the first time

785
00:54:32,139 --> 00:54:34,875
he would be the leader
of a sovereign community

786
00:54:34,875 --> 00:54:36,743
based on Islamic law.

787
00:54:37,411 --> 00:54:40,681
Yathrib would henceforth
become known as Medina.

788
00:54:42,216 --> 00:54:44,351
Muhammad arrives in Medina as

789
00:54:44,351 --> 00:54:46,720
somebody who was escaping danger.

790
00:54:47,254 --> 00:54:50,924
He's been invited there but
he doesn't know what to expect...

791
00:54:53,126 --> 00:54:57,831
So at each stage of his life,
there's a new challenge

792
00:54:58,332 --> 00:55:01,935
and obviously,
new fears and new doubts.

793
00:55:02,536 --> 00:55:06,507
And so, he started thinking
in terms of policy.

794
00:55:06,874 --> 00:55:08,675
In terms of strategy.

795
00:55:09,009 --> 00:55:11,044
In terms of tactics.

796
00:55:12,379 --> 00:55:17,050
And that's what ultimately
made him into a statesman.

797
00:55:17,918 --> 00:55:19,920
Because that's what statesmen do.

798
00:55:20,354 --> 00:55:23,123
Now unlike Jesus, or the Buddha

799
00:55:23,123 --> 00:55:25,492
who seem to have been purely
spiritual leaders

800
00:55:25,492 --> 00:55:27,694
with no temporal responsibilities whatever

801
00:55:27,928 --> 00:55:30,330
MUHAMMAD found himself now head of state.

802
00:55:30,597 --> 00:55:33,634
Having transferred the Muslim families

803
00:55:34,001 --> 00:55:36,136
from MECCA to Medina.

804
00:55:36,570 --> 00:55:39,006
He now had to make sure
they could survive there.

805
00:55:39,873 --> 00:55:42,910
The survival of the fledgling
community depended on

806
00:55:42,910 --> 00:55:46,180
its ability to defend itself
against attacks from Mecca.

807
00:55:47,614 --> 00:55:49,750
To respond to this possibility

808
00:55:49,750 --> 00:55:52,786
Muhammad developed
a novel political solution.

809
00:55:54,288 --> 00:55:57,424
He essentially establishes
a pact, an agreement

810
00:55:57,424 --> 00:55:59,893
sometimes it's called
the Constitution Of Medina.

811
00:56:00,394 --> 00:56:02,696
Whether you were a Pagan or a Muslim

812
00:56:03,197 --> 00:56:06,400
or a member of the Jewish tribes or
any other tribes in Medina

813
00:56:06,733 --> 00:56:08,969
you had to sign on to this pact.

814
00:56:09,603 --> 00:56:11,805
And the pact established that

815
00:56:12,005 --> 00:56:15,309
if there were ever an attack
on Medina from the outside

816
00:56:15,609 --> 00:56:18,512
all the inhabitants of the town
of would be responsible

817
00:56:18,612 --> 00:56:20,314
to defend the city.

818
00:56:20,814 --> 00:56:25,619
This way, Muhammad really developed
a revolutionary idea

819
00:56:25,919 --> 00:56:29,990
which was transcend
your tribal responsibilities

820
00:56:29,990 --> 00:56:31,992
your petty particularism

821
00:56:32,125 --> 00:56:36,063
and begin to think in larger terms,
as a entire community.

822
00:56:37,831 --> 00:56:40,801
Now this was a very fearful terrifying

823
00:56:40,934 --> 00:56:43,504
time for Muslims but nevertheless

824
00:56:43,604 --> 00:56:46,940
it was seen as a creative time when
faith was at its strongest.

825
00:56:47,474 --> 00:56:52,412
It's a creative act for Muslims
to look back at the

826
00:56:52,513 --> 00:56:56,550
Muslim community in Medina and
try to apply the

827
00:56:56,750 --> 00:56:59,753
ideals to their own society
so that they can

828
00:56:59,753 --> 00:57:03,290
reproduce something of the Prophet's
original spirit.

829
00:57:06,994 --> 00:57:13,767
I came here to this country and
I came with a feeling that

830
00:57:13,834 --> 00:57:18,705
I left back in my original country
in Iraq many memories

831
00:57:18,739 --> 00:57:20,207
many painful memories

832
00:57:20,207 --> 00:57:24,244
one of them that my grandfather as well as

833
00:57:24,945 --> 00:57:26,880
13 members of all my family

834
00:57:26,947 --> 00:57:31,385
were persecuted and imprisoned
by the dictator Saddam Hussein.

835
00:57:31,785 --> 00:57:35,088
That reminds me of the agony and pain

836
00:57:35,489 --> 00:57:39,226
many early immigrants went through
when they came to Medina.

837
00:57:40,661 --> 00:57:44,998
Like many other Muslims who have fled
persecution in their native countries

838
00:57:45,232 --> 00:57:48,468
Imam Hassan Qazwini, was drawn to America

839
00:57:48,468 --> 00:57:52,072
by the promise of religious freedom and
economic opportunity.

840
00:57:56,176 --> 00:57:58,178
He emigrated to Dearborn Michigan

841
00:57:58,412 --> 00:58:00,013
a community that boasts the highest

842
00:58:00,047 --> 00:58:03,383
per capita concentration of Muslims
in the United States

843
00:58:03,817 --> 00:58:07,821
where people are almost as likely
to speak Arabic as English.

844
00:58:09,423 --> 00:58:13,627
Hijra, migration,
it has a shining aspect for me.

845
00:58:14,027 --> 00:58:16,096
As well as for the Prophet and his

846
00:58:16,096 --> 00:58:19,032
companions who came with him
from Mecca to Medina.

847
00:58:20,434 --> 00:58:23,036
And that shining aspect was the freedom

848
00:58:23,170 --> 00:58:25,839
religious freedom that they faced in Medina.

849
00:58:27,341 --> 00:58:31,645
Muslims here in America, they feel
they are more free in practicing

850
00:58:31,678 --> 00:58:35,382
their religion than many
other Muslim countries.

851
00:58:44,892 --> 00:58:49,163
In many ways this whole immigration
process from Mecca to Medina very much

852
00:58:49,229 --> 00:58:53,233
parallels what's happened in my own city
here in Dearborn, in our own backyard.

853
00:58:53,567 --> 00:58:55,802
And I see it play out in
the hospital where I work.

854
00:59:05,145 --> 00:59:09,249
Najah Bazzy is a nurse
at Dearborn's Oakwood Hospital.

855
00:59:09,750 --> 00:59:11,965
She conducts training sessions
to help bridge

856
00:59:11,965 --> 00:59:15,085
the gap of understanding between
the hospital staff

857
00:59:15,489 --> 00:59:19,226
and their Muslim patients,
many of whom are immigrants.

858
00:59:20,294 --> 00:59:22,596
I know you're all nurses, and I know

859
00:59:22,963 --> 00:59:27,167
that you're in this profession,
just as I am, to serve, to do a good job.

860
00:59:28,502 --> 00:59:30,871
But it's real easy for us to get
caught up in our own baggage.

861
00:59:31,104 --> 00:59:35,209
We're all human and we all have
a certain set of preconceived notions

862
00:59:35,542 --> 00:59:37,744
just as you walk through
the door and you saw me

863
00:59:37,744 --> 00:59:39,847
for the first time, just as you
might have seen Alijah.

864
00:59:40,180 --> 00:59:45,452
In the sensitivity training inevitably,
they know very little about the faith of Islam.

865
00:59:46,019 --> 00:59:52,092
They think that the faith of Islam is
a very maybe terroristic, militant, barbaric

866
00:59:52,092 --> 00:59:54,094
spread by the sword faith.

867
00:59:55,128 --> 00:59:58,866
And so when they have a Muslim
up there talking about

868
00:59:59,366 --> 01:00:03,837
patient rights, dignity,
issues around health

869
01:00:04,271 --> 01:00:08,709
and illness, all of a sudden you see
all of these stereotypes that people

870
01:00:09,009 --> 01:00:12,813
have as part of, you know, the baggage
as we grow up, just kind of fall.

871
01:00:12,913 --> 01:00:16,683
When you transcend culture,
you arrive at a universal place

872
01:00:16,884 --> 01:00:20,287
where our humanness is all the same.
You grieve the same.

873
01:00:21,121 --> 01:00:22,789
We all cry when someone we love dies.

874
01:00:23,457 --> 01:00:27,394
When we deliver, those of us who deliver,
we all experience labor.

875
01:00:28,328 --> 01:00:33,233
Something happened in Dearborn that further
established a need for this kind of work

876
01:00:33,500 --> 01:00:36,570
and that was a huge immigration process
as a result of the Gulf War.

877
01:00:37,337 --> 01:00:42,409
As a critical care nurse, Najah Bazzy
often has to counsel patients with terminal

878
01:00:42,409 --> 01:00:47,681
illnesses, like this Iraqi immigrant who
has just been diagnosed with uterine cancer.

879
01:00:49,383 --> 01:00:51,451
I said to her what do you think you have?

880
01:00:51,485 --> 01:00:55,856
And she said I have an infection in
the uterus and they took it out.

881
01:00:55,989 --> 01:00:59,760
Maybe she's not hearing it the first time,
maybe she doesn't need to hear it.

882
01:00:59,927 --> 01:01:01,261
Maybe she can't hear it.

883
01:01:01,628 --> 01:01:03,330
They're just not saying
